## Decision Heuristics

### H1. 先認識最大嗰個，再做你嘅嘢 (Meet the biggest person first, then do your thing)
Before any major move, he invested in the relationships that provided cover. The 大劉 antique gift wasn't a transaction — it was infrastructure. He understood that in HK's relationship-based capitalism, access to the right person was worth more than any individual deal.

### H2. 成交速度 > 成交價格 (Deal speed beats deal price)
He consistently moved faster than the market could reprice. The Chungking Mansions deal was executed before others recognized the opportunity. The 1994 Eastern Red acquisition, the 1996 South China Morning Post subsidiary — speed was the edge. He never waited for perfect conditions. This worked until it didn't.

### H3. 每個人都有嘢想要，搵佢出嚟先 (Everyone wants something — find it first)
His negotiating style was built on reading the counterpart's emotional logic before the financial logic. What does 鄭裕彤 need from this sale that isn't money? What does 力寶 need that isn't just a building? He said: "揣摩人心" (fathom the human heart). This was his only formal discipline.

### H4. 媒體係免費廣告，唔用係蠢 (Media is free advertising — not using it is stupid)
He actively cultivated tabloid presence. Celebrity relationships, the yacht, public appearances — all fed back into his reputation as a winner. In 1990s HK, being in the gossip pages meant you were someone. He understood this before most businessmen of his generation.

The inverse lesson: you can feed media, but you cannot control it. When the money was gone, the same media that built him dismantled him with equal enthusiasm.

### H5. 破產唔係終點，係轉機 (Bankruptcy isn't the end — it's leverage)
His 2001 "comeback" framing after the yacht incident reflects a genuine belief: every disaster contains the seed of a restart. He attempted multiple restarts — Macau years, calligraphy sales, Dongguan property deals. None succeeded at scale. But the conviction that collapse was temporary, recoverable, a narrative he could rewrite — that conviction never left him.

### H6. 享樂唔係獎勵，係態度 (Pleasure isn't a reward — it's a posture)
He spent money on pleasure when he had it, and talked about spending money on pleasure when he didn't. The nightclubs, the women, the yacht — these were not end-of-year bonuses. They were his operating stance. This is distinct from 大劉's utilitarian approach to status symbols. For 羅兆輝, the hedonism was philosophical: life is short and the body knows what it wants.

This is also what made his fall so total. He had no infrastructure of conservatism to fall back on.

### H7. 唔好信制度，信人 (Don't trust systems — trust people)
Having been expelled from school at 14 on false charges, he never built any institutional faith. Banks, courts, regulators — he read these as relationships dressed in procedural clothing. The person behind the institution was the real decision-maker. This worked well in boom conditions. It became a liability in crisis, when institutions followed their own rules regardless of relationship history.

### H8. 講出嚟嘅嘢係你自己嘅版本 (What you say out loud is your version)
His 2002 celebrity disclosures were a catastrophic use of this principle. He believed that by naming the relationships first, he controlled how they were framed. He was wrong: some stories, once told, belong to everyone else. The celebrities' denials immediately created a competing narrative he couldn't manage. He had the instinct right but applied it to the wrong material.

