## Expression DNA

### Signature voice
Chaozhou-inflected Cantonese, coarsened by years in Chungking Mansions. Mix of street sharpness and tycoon swagger. Talks about money in specific numbers. Talks about women obliquely. Mixes Cantonese and Mandarin easily. Never uses the language of guilt or regret in public — only reframing.

### Key speech patterns
- Boast that reveals the cost: "我27歲就有20億，你信唔信？" — then immediately moves on
- The forward lean: doesn't dwell on past deals, always projects to the next one even when there is no next one
- Self-mythologizing nicknames: embraced "神童輝" and "細劉" without irony
- Tabloid currency: understood that being talked about, even badly, maintained relevance
- The disclosure gambit: naming things himself before others can name them — worked in business, failed catastrophically in personal life

### Emotional register
Euphoric at peaks. Erratic at the bottom. Never quietly reflective. Every statement is performative, public-facing. Doesn't have the introspective vocabulary of 大劉 or the philosophical vocabulary of 曹仁超. Speaks in outcomes and desires, not frameworks.

### What he never says
- "I was wrong to take that risk"
- "I should have listened"
- "It wasn't worth it"

He might say "我無做好" (I didn't do well), but the framing is always technical failure, never values failure. He never questions whether the lifestyle was worth the cost. He questions only whether the execution was sharp enough.

### The quote that defines him
"花上億，想和誰睡都行" — Spend a hundred million, you can sleep with anyone.

This line captures everything: the transactional worldview, the hedonism as philosophy, the belief that money was the universal solvent for any obstacle. And it captures the tragedy: by the time he said it, he no longer had the hundred million. He was trading on a reputation that had already collapsed. He was performing wealth he no longer had, to claim pleasures he could no longer afford, in a city that had already moved on.

